 its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."],[356,"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."],[315,"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."],[416,"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."],[592,"A **workflow package** is a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` file for moving a workflow between Hubs. Exports contain source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content/workflow hashes — never secret values. Imports publish the source as a new immutable bundle and create the workflow **disabled by default**, so an admin can configure and preflight it locally before enabling it. `validate` and `preview` let you check a package without writing anything."],[570,"A **workflow** is the unit of the Runyard catalog: a named, versioned definition of something an agent can do. Each workflow has a slug, a display name and description, input/output schemas, and a source program that the runner executes. In older code and database tables the same object is called a *capability* — that is the legacy/internal synonym; user-facing surfaces say workflow."],[112,"A card's `status` is only ever `pending` or `resolved`. What was decided and by what live in separate fields:"],[878,"A creator can make a card timed by supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt`, optionally with a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`) — via `POST /api/approvals` or the `create_approval` MCP tool:"],[1127,"A deployed Hub checks the public GitHub Releases API passively (outbound-only, `UPDATE_CHECK_ENABLED`, default on) and shows admins an update badge."],[235,"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."],[817,"A few endpoints are rate-limited per client IP (over the limit returns `429`):"],[103,"A gated side effect asking permission before it runs."],[145,"A held run is cancelled, never failed."],[251,"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."],[1259,"A minimal, real example"],[514,"A normal person or agent: read everything, run workflows, decide approvals. No admin or runner rights."],[1212,"A quality gate (tests, lint, typecheck, build, eval) failed inside the workflow."],[1203,"A queued run means no runner has claimed it — either no runner is online, or none matches the run's required tags / requested location (`local` vs `vps`/`remote`)."],[1195,"A run is in `waiting_approval`"],[1194,"A run is stuck in `queued`"],[462,"A run receives the union of:"],[385,"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."],[1204,"A runner is considered offline after \\~30 seconds without a heartbeat. If the runner should be online, check its service logs on the runner host:"],[972,"A running Hub also serves its own **client** install script at\n`https://hub.example.com/install.sh` (plus the CLI tarball at `/cli.tgz`). That\none installs the `runyard` CLI and `runyard-mcp` on a workstation — see\nthe CLI guide."],[2,"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."],[166,"A specific artifact."],[492,"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."],[274,"A usage record is one observed model call:"],[571,"A workflow definition carries:"],[56,"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."],[99,"A workflow paused at a gate; the decision releases or denies that step."],[322,"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."],[805,"Abandon the negotiation"],[1090,"Admin & updates"],[1242,"Admin actions (creating workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules) need `admin`; running workflows needs `api` or `mcp`; the runner protocol needs `runner`. Ask a Hub admin for a token with the right scopes."],[190,"Admin and setup views."],[249,"Admin readiness dry-run."],[935,"Admin-scoped commands:"],[611,"Admin; disables."],[638,"Admin; imports disabled."],[635,"Admin; nothing written."],[560,"Admin; who did what, most recent first."],[66,"Admin."],[69,"Admin."],[74,"Admin."],[77,"Admin."],[83,"Admin."],[86,"Admin."],[246,"Admin."],[442,"Admin."],[445,"Admin."],[448,"Admin."],[454,"Admin."],[481,"Admin."],[539,"Admin."],[548,"Admin."],[608,"Admin."],[626,"Admin."],[629,"Admin."],[632,"Admin."],[545,"Admin. `{name, scopes, expiresInDays?}`."],[478,"Admin. `{value, description?}`."],[439,"Admin. Body: `name`, `workflowSlug`, `cron` or `runAt`, `timezone`, `input`, `enabled`."],[602,"Admin. Inline source or `workflow.bundleId`."],[475,"Admin. Names and metadata only."],[542,"Admin. Scope vocabulary, presets, defaults."],[1296,"Admins can export a workflow as a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package file. It contains the workflow source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content hashes — never secret values."],[39,"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."],[40,"Agents, Skills & Knowledge"],[728,"Aliases are the same registry entries registered twice, so they always share\nthe canonical route's handler, auth, and scopes; in `openapi.json` each alias\ncarries `x-canonical-path`. Unversioned `/api/...` paths remain fully\nsupported — use whichever reads better. The legacy `/api/capabilities/*`\npaths are deprecated aliases of `/api/workflows/*` and get no `/api/v1` form;\nnew clients should say *workflow* everywhere."],[55,"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."],[46,"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."],[95,"An **approval** is a declared question with a declared consequence, presented to a human as a card in the web app, over Telegram, or through the API/MCP. Cards can hold a run before it executes (`waiting_approval`), pause a workflow mid-run at an engine gate, or simply record a decision. A run held on an approval waits indefinitely — waiting never fails it."],[840,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[111,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is treated as absent; such cards fall back to a heuristic ask explicitly marked `derived: true`, so a guessed question is never presented as an authored one."],[289,"An invalid budget is rejected with `400 budget_invalid` at creation (and surfaces as a preflight blocker in negotiation) — a requested cap is never silently dropped."],[976,"And the runner unit (`deploy/runyard-runner.service`):"],[801,"Answer questions: `input` is shallow-merged (a `null` value deletes a key; `replaceInput: true` replaces it), then re-preflighted"],[105,"Any ad-hoc approval raised via the API."],[45,"API & MCP"],[94,"API & MCP"],[201,"API & MCP"],[314,"API & MCP"],[355,"API & MCP"],[415,"API & MCP"],[459,"API & MCP"],[489,"API & MCP"],[569,"API & MCP"],[677,"API groups and `/api/v1` aliases"],[866,"Applied as a deny with your note attached; the workflow's own deny path decides what happens next."],[867,"Applied as a deny; the workflow's deny path decides what happens next."],[88,"Approval cards - kinds, the ask contract, resolutions, timed approvals with fallbacks, and per-kind consequences."],[193,"Approval cards carry `deepLink` (the card) and `deepLinkRun` (the linked run), and their `context` includes workflow and run deep links."],[838,"Approval cards with buttons"],[1146,"Approval gating"],[182,"Approval inbox / one card."],[520,"Approval inboxes and bots that only decide."],[87,"Approvals"],[680,"Approvals"],[906,"Approvals"],[1070,"Approvals"],[38,"Approvals — put human checkpoints in front of dangerous work."],[830,"Approvals and Telegram"],[877,"Approvals are blocking by default: with no timer configured, nothing happens until someone decides, and a linked run is held open indefinitely."],[554,"Approvals-scoped Telegram session."],[857,"Approve"],[788,"Approve — a held run is released"],[530,"Approving from Telegram uses `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp&#x60;, which verifies Telegram's signed init data against the configured bot and allowlisted users, then issues a session scoped to **`approvals` only** — narrower than any token session. A Telegram session can list and resolve approval cards but cannot start runs or touch admin surfaces."],[1072,"Artifacts"],[666,"Ask the Hub's administrator for a scoped access token (admins issue them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`). Agents typically need `api` and/or `mcp` — nothing more. Send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every HTTP call, or configure it for the MCP server. Never ask for or expect the bootstrap/admin token."],[1092,"Assistant"],[775,"Audit log (admin)"],[650,"Auth"],[644,"Auth expectations"],[674,"Authenticate, discover, and drive workflow runs over the Runyard Hub's HTTP API."],[675,"Authentication"],[1256,"Authoring workflows"],[37,"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."],[101,"Autonomous recovery gave up; a human records how to proceed."],[1035,"Back this directory up. The runner workspace, by contrast, is disposable\nscratch space — outputs and event traces are uploaded to the Hub as artifacts."],[483,"Bearer-token authentication, the scope vocabulary and presets (including read-only), the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."],[376,"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard can run a **deterministic preflight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."],[1000,"Bind address (default `127.0.0.1`)"],[486,"Bootstrap token"],[836,"Bot setup"],[1265,"Both operations require an admin-scoped token."],[551,"Browser session bootstrap (rate-limited)."],[487,"Browser sessions"],[270,"Budgets"],[285,"Budgets are hard stops, not advisories:"],[640,"Building agents on Runyard"],[1124,"Builds and pushes GHCR `hub` and `runner` container images behind the same two gates, and records both image digests as a release artifact."],[119,"By default a card is blocking: nothing happens until someone decides. Supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt` at creation makes it a **timed approval**:"],[326,"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."],[760,"Cancel; re-queue with same/edited input; merge a successful isolated run into its target branch"],[710,"Canonical"],[312,"Capacity and pool"],[271,"Capture paths: what is metered today"],[852,"Cards are posted to the configured chat with inline buttons (see below)."],[899,"Cards can deep-link into the Hub as a Telegram WebApp. `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp` exchanges the WebApp's signed init data for a browser session that is limited to the `approvals` scope — a Telegram identity can review and resolve approval cards, and nothing else. Full app access always requires a real access token."],[47,"Catalog"],[1088,"Catalog"],[1275,"Catalog grouping (for example `Examples`, `Operations`)."],[889,"Chat (group or DM) where approval cards are posted."],[1216,"Check run diagnostics; fix workflow config or runner setup."],[1104,"CI pipeline"],[364,"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."],[984,"claims runs and executes them; workspace volume at `/workspace`"],[1208,"Class"],[557,"Clears the session cookie."],[847,"